revision.text:
'''All Power to the People: Black Panthers at 50''' is an [[Art exhibition|exhibition]] put on by the [[Oakland Museum of California]] from October 8, 2016 to February 26, 2017. The exhibit was organized by [[Oakland Museum of California|OMCA]]'s senior curator [[René De Guzman]].
The exhibition celebrates the 50th anniversary of the founding of the [[Black Panther Party]], combining objects which examine lesser known works of the Black Panther party, such as the [[Free Breakfast for Children|Free Breakfast for School Children Program]] and, founders [[Huey Newton]] and [[Bobby Seale]]'s, [[Ten-Point Program]], with pieces of [[contemporary art]] by artists whose work inspires questions about [[Racial inequality in the United States|racial inequality]] 50 years later.<ref name="LATIMES">{{cite news|last1=Bradner|first1=Liesl|title='All Power to the People' explores the often misunderstood history of the Black Panther movement|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-ca-cm-black-panthers-art-20161016-snap-htmlstory.html|accessdate=18 November 2017|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=October 14, 2016}}</ref>
== Participants == ''Power to the People'' featured work by contemporary artists [[Sadie Barnette]], [[Hank Willis Thomas]], [[Carrie Mae Weems]], [[Mark T. Emerson|Mark Teemer]], [[Trevor Paglen]] and [[David Huffman (artist)|David Huffman]], among others.
==Historical Objects== * ''Afro-American Solidarity with Oppressed People of the World'' – poster of a warrior by Minister of Culture for the Black Panther Party 1967-1980, [[Emory Douglas]].<ref name="Laney Tower" /> * ''Huey Newton photograph'' – the iconic image of Huey Newton enthroned in a wicker chair composed by [[Eldridge Cleaver]] and photographed by [[Blair Stapp]] in 1967.<ref name="AFROPUNK">{{cite web|last1=Candy|first1=Eye|title=Black Panther Poster references Iconic Huey P. Newton Poster|url=http://afropunk.com/2017/06/black-panther-poster-references-iconic-huey-p-newton-picture/|website=AFROPUNK|publisher=AFROPUNK, Inc.|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref><ref name="Laney Tower" /> * ''Jail Door'' – door to a cell that once held Black Panthers, courtesy of the [[Oakland Police Department]].<ref name="KTVU">{{cite news|last1=Torrez|first1=Andre|title=Oakland's Black Panthers at 50 exhibit extended through Black History Month|url=http://www.ktvu.com/news/black-history-month/oaklands-black-panthers-at-50-exhibit-extended-throughout-black-history-month|accessdate=20 November 2017|publisher=KTVU/Fox 2|date=February 2, 2017}}</ref> * ''Oakland Panther photograph'' – image of chic young black man, holding a rifle, in front of the Oakland Police Department<ref name="KTVU" /> * ''Ten Point Platform and Program'' – the rough draft, handwritten by Bobby Seale in 1966, of the founding document of the Black Panther Party<ref name="San Francisco Chronicle">{{cite news|last1=Whiting|first1=Sam|title=Oakland Museum takes Bobby Seale back where Black Panthers began|url=http://www.sfchronicle.com/art/article/Oakland-Museum-takes-Bobby-Seale-back-where-Black-9967498.php|accessdate=18 November 2017|agency=San Francisco Chronicle|publisher=Hearst Corporation|date=October 14, 2016}}</ref>
==Art Works== * ''100 Unarmed African Americans Killed by Police in 2014'' is a list of names cut from black paper by [[Ellen Bepp]].<ref name="East Bay Express">{{cite news|last1=Burke|first1=Sarah|title=The Oakland Museum of California's Homage to the Black Panther Party|url=https://www.eastbayexpress.com/oakland/the-oakland-museum-of-californias-homage-to-the-black-panther-party/Content?oid=5004805|accessdate=27 November 2017|publisher=East Bay Express|date=October 11, 2016}}</ref><ref name="Medium">{{cite web|last1=Bernier|first1=Mia|title=Friday Night Learning|url=https://medium.com/@miabernier/friday-night-learning-779c1c0da221|website=Medium|accessdate=27 November 2017}}</ref> * ''The Black Panthers: Portraits from an Unfinished Revolution'' is a selection of contemporary photographic images of former Black Panther Party members by [[Bryan Shih]].<ref name="7x7">{{cite web|last1=Medina|first1=Sarah|title=All Power to the People: OMCA Celebrates 50 Years of the Black Panthers|url=http://www.7x7.com/all-power-to-the-people-omca-celebrates-50-years-of-the-black-panthers-2038327593.html|website=7x7|publisher=Natalie Wages|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref> * ''Capture of Angela'' is an [[Archival digital print|archival pigment print]] of conceptual artist [[Carrie Mae Weems]]' reenactment of the 1970 arrest of activist [[Angela Davis]].<ref name="http://goldengatexpress.org/2017/02/22/black-panther-party-exhibit-extended-due-to-high-demand/">{{cite news|last1=Long|first1=Nevin|title=Black Panther Party exhibit extended due to high demand|url=http://goldengatexpress.org/2017/02/22/black-panther-party-exhibit-extended-due-to-high-demand/|accessdate=20 November 2017|publisher=SF State|date=February 22, 2017}}</ref> * ''MLK'' is an [[Afrofuturist]] painting depicting [[Martin Luther King, Jr.]]'s funeral procession with black mourners in space suits by [[David Huffman (artist)|David Huffman]].<ref name="Laney Tower" /> * ''Proposal for a Monument to Huey P. Newton for the Alameda County Courthouse'' is a bronze sculpture by [[Sam Durant]] which replicates the wicker chair from an iconic photo of Huey Newton.<ref name="Laney Tower">{{cite news|last1=Carpenter|first1=Sarah|title=Echoes: Oakland exhibit traces history of Black Panthers Party|url=http://thelaneytower.com/2016/10/13/revolution-in-our-lifetime/|accessdate=19 November 2017|publisher=Laney Tower|date=October 16, 2016}}</ref> * ''We The People'' is a quilt made of prison uniforms by [[Hank Willis Thomas]].<ref name="Tofu">{{cite web|last1=St. John|first1=Scott|title=Culture Moves the Message Forward|url=http://tofuartsf.blogspot.com/2016/11/culture-moves-message-forward.html|website=Tofu's Art Blog|publisher=Scott St. John|accessdate=27 November 2017}}</ref>
== Reception and criticism == The timely-ness of the exhibit was remarked on in several exhibition reviews. [[Jeff Greenwald]] said "From [[Black Lives Matter]] to quarterback [[Colin Kaepernick]]'s bended knee, the Black Panthers' political legacy remains alive in America's ongoing dialogue about race, justice and privilege."<ref name="Smithsonian">{{cite journal|last1=Greenwald|first1=Jeff|title=The Black Panthers Were Founded 50 Years Ago, and Their Influence Hasn't Waned |journal=Smithsonian Magazine Online|date=October 28, 2016|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/black-panthers-were-founded-50-years-ago-and-their-influence-hasnt-waned-180960940/|accessdate=22 November 2017}}</ref>
