The '''Benty Grange hanging bowl''' is a fragmentary [[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo-Saxon]] artefact from the 7th century AD. All that remains are two escutcheons; a third disintegrated soon after excavation, and no longer survives. The escutcheons were found in 1848, alongside the better-known [[Benty Grange helmet]], by the [[Antiquarian|antiquary]] [[Thomas Bateman]] in a [[tumulus]] at the [[Benty Grange]] farm in the English county of [[Derbyshire]]. They were undoubtedly buried as part of an entire [[hanging bowl]], placed in what appears to have been the burial mound of a high-status warrior.

What remains of one escutcheon belongs to [[Museums Sheffield]] and in 2018 was displayed at [[Weston Park Museum]].{{sfn|Museums Sheffield escutcheon}} The other is held by the [[Ashmolean Museum]] at the [[University of Oxford]]; as of 2018 it is not on display.{{sfn|Ashmolean Museum}}

==Description==
[[File:Benty Grange finds - Llewellynn Jewitt watercolour.jpg|thumb|alt=Colour image of a Llewellynn Jewitt watercolour depicting the Benty Grange hanging bowl escutcheons and associated finds|A contemporary watercolour by [[Llewellynn Jewitt]] depicts the surviving escutcheons, top, fragments of the third escutcheon, second-to-bottom row, and associated finds.]]
The two surviving escutcheons are made of [[Vitreous enamel|enamelled]] bronze and are {{convert|40|mm|abbr=on}} in diameter.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|2005|p=119}} They have the same design and plain frames, parts of which survive.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|2005|p=119}} Both escutcheons are fragmentary; enough survives of each for the design to be reconstructed,{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|2005|p=119}} and, because of overlapping segments, for it to be certain that they represent two distinct pieces.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|1974|p=250 n.5}} Whether they are hook escutcheons, associated with the suspension hooks on the exterior of the bowl, or basal discs, placed at the base of the interior, is uncertain, but a ring on the back of one fragment suggests an association with the suspension chains, and a contemporary watercolour by [[Llewellynn Jewitt]] seems to show that a hook may have been present at excavation.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|2005|p=119}} The decomposed enamel background appears yellow to the eye,{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|2005|pp=77, 119}} as it did when excavated.{{sfn|Bateman|1849|p=277}}{{sfn|Bateman|1855|p=160}}{{sfn|Bateman|1861|p=29}} A red-yellow colour scheme has also been suggested,{{sfn|Henry|1936|p=236}}{{sfn|Haseloff|1990|p=162}} but on minimal and possibly incorrect evidence.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|2005|pp=77, 119}} As sampling of the enamel was not permitted when the Sheffield escutcheon was analysed at the museum in 1968, however, the all-yellow hypothesis is not definitive.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|2005|p=77}}

The reconstructed design shows three "ribbon-style fish or [[dolphin]]-like creatures", each biting the tail of the animal ahead of it.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|2005|p=119}} The bodies are yellow like the background, and defined by their outlines.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|1974|p=250 n.5}} They are limbless, the tails curled in a circle, and the jaws both long and curved; where the tails should pass through the jaws of the animals behind, gaps appear, creating slight separations between segments of tail.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|2005|p=119}} Each animal has a small eye shaped like a pointed oval.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|2005|p=119}} The outer borders of the discs, the plain frames, and the contours and eyes of the animals, are all tinned or silvered.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|2005|p=119}}

Surviving records of the third escutcheon indicate that it was of a different style and size.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|2005|p=119}}{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|1974|p=250 n.5}} Drawings by Bateman and Jewitt show it with a scroll pattern and small piece of frame.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|1974|p=250 n.5}}{{sfn|Bateman|1849|p=277}}{{sfn|Bateman|1861|pp=29–30}} It appears to have been about half the size of the other two, and may have originally been placed at the bottom of the hanging bowl.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|2005|p=119}}

The escutcheons were undoubtedly part of an entire hanging bowl when buried.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|2005|p=119}} Nothing else survives.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|2005|p=119}} The mass of corroded chainwork discovered six feet away, which survives only in illustrations by Jewitt and descriptions by Bateman,{{sfn|Museums Sheffield chainwork 1}}{{sfn|Museums Sheffield chainwork 2}} is unlikely to be related; although a large and intricate chain was found with a cauldron from [[Sutton Hoo]], the Benty Grange chains appear dissimilar.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|1974|p=250 n.6}} They were also likely too heavy to have been used to suspend the hanging bowl.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|1974|p=250 n.6}}

==Parallels==
[[File:DurhamAII10 folio 2r INI.png|thumb|upright|alt=Colour photograph of the illustrated INI monogram from the Durham Gospel Fragment|The INI monogram in the [[Gospel Book Fragment (Durham Cathedral Library, A. II. 10.)|Durham Gospel Fragment]] contains similar fish-like creatures.]]
The animal designs on the Benty Grange hanging bowl are paralleled by designs on other escutcheons, and even more closely by designs on medieval [[illuminated manuscript]]s.{{sfn|Henry|1936|p=236}}{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|2005|p=120}} Three escutcheons from a hanging bowl found in [[Faversham]] show animals that also look like dolphins,{{sfn|British Museum Faversham 1}}{{sfn|British Museum Faversham 2}}{{sfn|British Museum Faversham 3}} but with more developed bodies;{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|2005|p=120}} a better parallel is with a disc found near the [[Lullingstone]] hanging bowl that is also decorated with dolphin-like creatures.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|2005|pp=72, 120, 175, 428}}

Despite the similarities with other escutcheon and disc designs, several manuscript illustrations are more closely related to the Benty Grange designs.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|2005|p=120}} Bateman remarked on this as early as 1861, "shrewdly" as it turned out,{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|1974|pp=224–225}} noting that similar patterns were used in "several manuscripts of the VIIth Century, for the purpose of decorating the initial letters."{{sfn|Bateman|1861|p=29}} In particular, the mid-seventh-century [[Gospel Book Fragment (Durham Cathedral Library, A. II. 10.)|Durham Gospel Fragment]] contains two similar fish-like motifs contained within the lateral stroke of the INI [[monogram]] that introduces the [[Gospel of Mark]].{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|1974|p=250 n.5}}

==Discovery==
[[File:Benty Grange - geograph.org.uk - 311410.jpg|thumb|alt=Colour photograph of the Benty Grange Farm|Benty Grange Farm, in the parish of [[Monyash]] in the [[Derbyshire Dales]] district]]
The hanging bowl was discovered on 3 May 1848 during an excavation on the [[Benty Grange]] farm in Derbyshire,{{sfn|Bateman|1861|p=28}} in what is now the [[Peak District]] National Park.{{sfn|Lester|1987|p=34}} It was found by [[Thomas Bateman]], an archaeologist and antiquarian who was nicknamed "The Barrow Knight" for his excavation of more than 500 [[tumulus|barrows]].{{sfn|Bateman|1861|p=vi}}{{sfn|Howarth|1899|p=v}} Bateman described Benty Grange as "a high and bleak situation";{{sfn|Bateman|1861|p=28}} its barrow, which still survives, is prominently located by a major Roman road, now the [[A515 road|A515]], possibly in order to display the burial to passing travellers.{{sfn|Brown|2017|p=21}} It may have also been designed to share the skyline with   two other nearby monuments, [[Arbor Low]] [[Stone circles|stone circle]] and [[Gib Hill]] barrow.{{sfn|Brown|2017|p=21}} The Benty Grange barrow comprises a circular central mound approximately {{convert|15|m|ft|abbr=on}} in diameter and {{convert|0.6|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} high, an encircling fosse about {{convert|1|m|ft|abbr=on}} wide and {{convert|0.3|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} deep, and outer penannular banks around {{convert|3|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} wide and {{convert|0.2|m|ft|abbr=on}} high.{{sfn|Historic England Benty Grange}} The entire structure measures approximately {{convert|23|by|22|m|ft|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Historic England Benty Grange}}

Unnoted in Bateman's account is that he was likely not the first person to dig up the grave.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|1974|p=229}} The fact that the objects were found in two clusters separated by six feet, and that other objects that normally accompany a helmet were absent, such as a sword and shield, suggests that the grave had previously been looted.{{sfn|Bruce-Mitford|1974|p=229}} Being so large it may alternatively or additionally have contained two inhumations, only one of which was discovered by Bateman.{{sfn|Historic England Benty Grange}}

The Benty Grange barrow was designated a [[scheduled monument]] on 23 October 1970.{{sfn|Historic England Benty Grange}} The list entry notes that "[a]lthough the centre of Benty Grange [barrow] has been partially disturbed by excavation, the monument is otherwise undisturbed and retains significant archaeological remains."{{sfn|Historic England Benty Grange}} It goes on to note that further excavation would yield new information.{{sfn|Historic England Benty Grange}} The nearby farm was renovated between 2012 and 2014;{{sfn|Peak District Applications|2012}}{{sfn|BentyGrange Twitter|2014}} as of 2018 it is rented out as a holiday cottage.{{sfn|Peak Venues Benty Grange}}

